<hl>
<seg id=1> China Plans to Reclaim One Million Hectares of Land From Sea in Next Century to Find Place for Population of 20-30 Million </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (France News Agency, Beijing, Telegram) The English language "China Daily" reported yesterday that China plans to reclaim land from coastal areas in the next century to find a place for a population of 20-30 million. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> In a fill meeting held in Xiaoshan, Zhejiang Province, experts revealed that the government hopes to reclaim one million hectares of land from the sea along the 18,000 km coastal area in the next 40-50 years.  </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> According to the "China Daily", a population of 20-30 million would reside in those areas in the next century.  </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> The newspaper quoted professor Yu Zhiyin (transliteration) as saying: "Technically, China has no problems in achieving its ocean-filling objectives. The problem is insufficient funds." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> According to the news, even if the project causes serious environmental problems, "it is still a magic formula for alleviating the shortage of land resources in the next century, especially in light of the huge population of China." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Related projects could also promote new industries and employment opportunities.  </seg>
<seg id=8> China plans to invest in infrastructure to eliminate the effect of the Asian financial crisis.  </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Zuo Zhongmo (transliteration), assistant secretary at the meeting, said that: "This issue does not just concern agriculture. The land can be used for comprehensive development purposes in multiple fields, including forestry, industry, and tourism." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> Although China promotes a "one child policy," it is expected that the population of China will continue to grow, peaking at 1.6 billion people in the middle of the next century.  </seg>
<seg id=11> Currently, China has a population of 1.23 billion people.  </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> Over 90% of the population is crowded onto one-third of the national territory.  </seg>
</p>
